defs.name: NewEvents
defs.docs: Emitted when new events arrive from the OS to be processed.

defs.name: WindowEvent
defs.docs: Emitted when the OS sends an event to a winit window.

defs.name: DeviceEvent

defs.name: UserEvent
defs.docs: Emitted when an event is sent from [`EventLoopProxy::send_event`](crate::event_loop::EventLoopProxy::send_event)

defs.name: Suspended
defs.docs: Emitted when the application has been suspended.

defs.name: Resumed
defs.docs: Emitted when the application has been resumed.

defs.name: MainEventsCleared
defs.docs:
Emitted when all of the event loop's input events have been processed and redraw processing
 is about to begin.

defs.name: RedrawRequested
defs.docs: Emitted after `MainEventsCleared` when a window should be redrawn.

defs.name: RedrawEventsCleared
defs.docs:
Emitted after all `RedrawRequested` events have been processed and control flow is about to
 be taken away from the program. If there are no `RedrawRequested` events, it is emitted
 immediately after `MainEventsCleared`.

defs.name: LoopDestroyed
defs.docs: Emitted when the event loop is being shut down.

defs.name: to_static
defs.docs:
If the event doesn't contain a reference, turn it into an event with a `'static` lifetime.
 Otherwise, return `None`.

defs.name: ResumeTimeReached
defs.docs:
Sent if the time specified by `ControlFlow::WaitUntil` has been reached. Contains the
 moment the timeout was requested and the requested resume time. The actual resume time is
 guaranteed to be equal to or after the requested resume time.

defs.name: WaitCancelled
defs.docs:
Sent if the OS has new events to send to the window, after a wait was requested. Contains
 the moment the wait was requested and the resume time, if requested.

defs.name: Poll
defs.docs:
Sent if the event loop is being resumed after the loop's control flow was set to
 `ControlFlow::Poll`.

defs.name: Init
defs.docs: Sent once, immediately after `run` is called. Indicates that the loop was just initialized.

defs.name: StartCause
defs.docs: Describes the reason the event loop is resuming.

defs.name: Calibrated
defs.docs:
On iOS, the force is calibrated so that the same number corresponds to
 roughly the same amount of pressure on the screen regardless of the
 device.

defs.name: Normalized
defs.docs:
If the platform reports the force as normalized, we have no way of
 knowing how much pressure 1.0 corresponds to  we know it's the maximum
 amount of force, but as to how much force, you might either have to
 press really really hard, or not hard at all, depending on the device.

defs.name: normalized
defs.docs:
Returns the force normalized to the range between 0.0 and 1.0 inclusive.
 Instead of normalizing the force, you should prefer to handle
 `Force::Calibrated` so that the amount of force the user has to apply is
 consistent across devices.

defs.name: event_loop
defs.docs: The `EventLoop` struct and assorted supporting types, including `ControlFlow`.

defs.name: EventLoop
defs.docs:
Provides a way to retrieve events from the system and from the windows that were registered to
 the events loop.

defs.name: EventLoopWindowTarget
defs.docs: Target that associates windows with an `EventLoop`.

defs.name: Poll
defs.docs:
When the current loop iteration finishes, immediately begin a new iteration regardless of
 whether or not new events are available to process. For web, events are sent when
 `requestAnimationFrame` fires.

defs.name: Wait
defs.docs: When the current loop iteration finishes, suspend the thread until another event arrives.

defs.name: WaitUntil
defs.docs:
When the current loop iteration finishes, suspend the thread until either another event
 arrives or the given time is reached.

defs.name: Exit
defs.docs:
Send a `LoopDestroyed` event and stop the event loop. This variant is *sticky* - once set,
 `control_flow` cannot be changed from `Exit`, and any future attempts to do so will result
 in the `control_flow` parameter being reset to `Exit`.

defs.name: ControlFlow
defs.docs: Set by the user callback given to the `EventLoop::run` method.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Builds a new event loop with a `()` as the user event type.

defs.name: with_user_event
defs.docs: Builds a new event loop.

defs.name: run
defs.docs:
Hijacks the calling thread and initializes the winit event loop with the provided
 closure. Since the closure is `'static`, it must be a `move` closure if it needs to
 access any data from the calling context.

defs.name: create_proxy
defs.docs: Creates an `EventLoopProxy` that can be used to dispatch user events to the main event loop.

defs.name: available_monitors
defs.docs: Returns the list of all the monitors available on the system.

defs.name: primary_monitor
defs.docs: Returns the primary monitor of the system.

defs.name: EventLoopProxy
defs.docs: Used to send custom events to `EventLoop`.

defs.name: send_event
defs.docs:
Send an event to the `EventLoop` from which this proxy was created. This emits a
 `UserEvent(event)` event in the event loop, where `event` is the value passed to this
 function.

defs.name: EventLoopClosed
defs.docs:
The error that is returned when an `EventLoopProxy` attempts to wake up an `EventLoop` that
 no longer exists. Contains the original event given to `send_event`.

defs.name: ByteCountNotDivisibleBy4
defs.docs:
Produced when the length of the `rgba` argument isn't divisible by 4, thus `rgba` can't be

defs.name: DimensionsVsPixelCount
defs.docs:
Produced when the number of pixels (`rgba.len() / 4`) isn't equal to `width * height`.
 At least one of your arguments is incorrect.

defs.name: OsError
defs.docs: Produced when underlying OS functionality failed to create the icon

defs.name: bit_depth
defs.docs:
Returns the bit depth of this video mode, as in how many bits you have
 available per color. This is generally 24 bits or 32 bits on modern
 systems, depending on whether the alpha channel is counted or not.

defs.name: refresh_rate
defs.docs:
Returns the refresh rate of this video mode. **Note**: the returned
 refresh rate is an integer approximation, and you shouldn't rely on this
 value to be exact.
